## Relationship with LeetCode 104

LeetCode **104 (Maximum Depth)** returns:

```java
return 1 + Math.max(left, right);
```

LeetCode **110** uses the same idea but adds one extra condition:

```java
if(Math.abs(left - right) > 1)
    return -1;
```

So, **110 is an extension of 104**.

---

## Key Learning

* A balanced tree means every node satisfies:

```text
|Left Height - Right Height| ≤ 1
```

* Calculate height and balance **together**.
* Use `-1` as a special value to represent an unbalanced subtree.
* This avoids recalculating heights multiple times.

---

## Common Mistakes

❌ Solving using `maxDepth()` for every node.

This leads to repeated calculations and **O(n²)** complexity.

---

❌ Forgetting early termination.

Always write:

```java
if(left == -1)
    return -1;

if(right == -1)
    return -1;
```

If a subtree is already unbalanced, there is no need to continue.

---

❌ Forgetting to check the height difference.

Always write:

```java
if(Math.abs(left - right) > 1)
    return -1;
```

---

❌ Returning height even when the subtree is unbalanced.

Return:

```java
-1
```

to indicate failure.

---

## Pattern Recognition

Whenever a tree problem asks you to:

* Compute height
* Compare left and right subtree
* Return information from child nodes
* Stop early when a condition fails

Think:

```java
left = solve(root.left);

right = solve(root.right);

if(condition fails)
    return specialValue;

return combine(left, right);
```

This is the **Bottom-Up Recursion Pattern**.

---

## Difference Between Top-Down and Bottom-Up

| Top-Down                                    | Bottom-Up                       |
| ------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| Recalculates subtree heights multiple times | Computes each subtree only once |
| O(n²)                                       | O(n)                            |
| Less efficient                              | Interview-preferred solution    |

---

## Takeaway

The key idea is to compute the **height and balance status together** using a single recursive function. Every subtree returns either its height or `-1` if it is already unbalanced. This allows the parent to stop immediately when an imbalance is detected, resulting in an efficient **O(n)** solution. This **Bottom-Up Recursion Pattern** is one of the most important techniques for Binary Tree interview problems.
